3. Intensifiers - 
Use words like "really" and "very" to describe experiences

Basic intensifiers

We use intensifiers - words like "very" and "really" 
- to strengthen adjectives ("friendly", "difficult", "great").
The people here are very friendly.
The test was so difficult.
We had a really great time at Glastonbury.

The president is a very important person.
"very" intensifies the meaning of the word it goes with.

She's such a good friend. She's so supportive.
We use "such" with a noun phrase (as in "such a good friend"), 
and we use "so" with an adjective (as in "so supportive").

The food at the festival was so tasty!
We use "so" with an adjective.

My hometown is really small.
"really" intensifies the meaning of the word it goes with.

Advanced intensifiers

These are some more advanced intensifiers. 
They indicate that something is done to a high degree or to the fullest degree.

High degree
extremely, incredibly, highly

Fullest degree
completely, absolutely, totally

absolutely
I am absolutely delighted to win this award, 
but I couldn't have done it without the help of my co-workers.

ompletely
The festival was completely different from what I expected. 
There was so much to see and do!

I had a great time in Seoul. The street food was absolutely amazing.
"absolutely" intensifies the meaning of "amazing".

Some events at the Edinburgh Festival are completely free.

Be careful when using "very"
We use "very" with adjectives like "big". 
We don't usually use "very" with stronger adjectives like "enormous" 
(which means "very big"). With strong adjectives like "enormous", 
we use intensifiers like "really", "absolutely", "completely" and so on.

very big, very small, very good, very bad 
absolutely enormous, absolutely tiny, really great, completely awful

The restaurant had a nice atmosphere, but the food was completely awful.
With strong adjectives like "awful", we use intensifiers like "really" or 
"completely", but not "very".

Have you ever been to Dubai? The shopping malls are absolutely enormous!

extremely
Although they didn't reach the final this time, 
I'm extremely proud of this group of players.

highly
Take these painkillers twice a day. 
They're highly effective, so you should feel better in a few days.

My daughter is extremely excited about going to Glastonbury.
We use "extremely" with a strong adjective like "excited".

He is very intelligent.
"highly" is a more formal synonym of "very".

incredibly
In many countries, weddings can be incredibly expensive.

totally
Don't worry if you feel stressed sometimes, that's totally normal.

Even today, The Beatles are still incredibly popular.
"incredibly" has a similar meaning to "very".

No worries, that's totally fine.
"totally" is used before the adjective "fine".

Using intensifiers with particular adjectives

Some intensifiers pair only with particular adjectives and they cannot be used interchangeably.

highly
skilled, unlikely, recommended, paid

totally, completely, absolutely 
new, different, dry, free, right 

extremely, incredibly
easy, expensive, busy, helpful, powerful

I wasn't sure what to do but I took your advice. It turns out you were absolutely right.
"absolutely right" is an example of words that pair up.

I'd heard this restaurant was hard to find, but your directions were incredibly easy to follow.

Going to that music festival was a completely new experience for me.

Of course, you are absolutely right.
This old Italian recipe is incredibly easy.
Rock and pop music are completely different.

The festival was totally awesome.

Experts think that an agreement between the two sides is highly... unlikely

I'm not sure if I can help you. I'm extremely busy at the moment.

Snow in summer is highly unlikely.
My boss is always extremely busy.
Dude, that movie was totally awesome!

When painting a wall, you should wait until the first coat is...
completely dry before adding the second coat.
Bringing your own food and drink is not absolutely necessary.
a highly successful writer and director.

Don't fold the laundry until it's completely dry.
All of her students became highly successful.
For some jobs, English skills are absolutely essential.

I'd heard this restaurant was hard to find, but your directions were incredibly easy to follow.
Thanks for your advice. You were absolutely right.

This weekend, a storm is highly likely.
Entry to some small festivals is completely free.
VIP passes can be incredibly expensive.
Yeah, we had a really great time. The headliners were absolutely amazing.
She is highly intelligent.
This new magazine doesn't cost anything - it's completely free!
Thank you very much, you've been extremely helpful.
As part of his MBA, he's reading a book about the habits of highly successful people.
Regular exercise and a balanced diet are absolutely essential for a healthy life.
Please tell me the truth. I want you to be totally honest with me.
These cameras may be small and light but they are incredibly powerful.

VOCABULARY
absolutely

completely

extremely

highly

incredibly

totally

