4. Reading about the Fringe Festival - Read about a culture festival in Scotland

You are going to read a guide for attending a major festival in Scotland. 
Before you start, have a look at the words and phrases below that you will 
find in the text.

the arts (music, theatre, dance, etc.)
a big name (a famous person)
a DJ set (a group of songs played by a DJ)
energetic (full of energy)
to miss out (to not join an activity)
to be packed with (to be full of)
spectacles (shows or performances)
to take place (to happen)
unpredictable (surprising or hard to predict)
a venue (an event location)

A Traveller’s Guide to the Edinburgh Fringe Festival
Would you like to go to the Edinburgh Fringe? 
This blog post will tell you everything you need to know 
about this incredibly fun and popular arts festival!

What is the Edinburgh Fringe Festival?
The Edinburgh Fringe is the world’s biggest arts festival. 
It takes place in the capital of Scotland every August. 
It is 3 weeks long, and is utterly packed with events. 
Last year the festival was bigger than ever, with 53,000 performances! 
There are 300 venues across the city, but because Edinburgh is quite small, 
it’s easy to find your way around!

What types of performers will I see?
The festival is completely open, which means that absolutely anyone can perform. 
If you attend, you’ll see a variety of different spectacles, 
from frightfully funny comedy shows to extremely energetic DJ sets and 
interesting plays. Before you go you should decide which events you want to 
see, as there is a lot to discover.

What can I eat at the festival?
Another reason to attend the Edinburgh Fringe festival is the food! 
There are plenty of meal options in the street markets, 
and don’t forget to visit the food trucks! 
You can explore the streets of Edinburgh, and find absolutely any dish you want.

What's the weather like?
Edinburgh is beautiful but the Scottish weather is very unpredictable. 
You will spend a lot of time outside, so if I were you,
I’d bring sun cream and also wellies - there could be a lot of rain!

How much does it cost?
You can book your tickets online. 
Some events are totally free, but most tickets cost £10 - 30. 
The headliners and big names might even cost more. 
Accommodation can be incredibly expensive, so you should book in advance.

If you don’t already have your tickets for this year’s Edinburgh Fringe, 
what are you waiting for? 
It’s going to be even bigger and better than last year, and trust me, you 
don’t want to miss out!

Many texts use paragraphs with headers to organise information into small chunks. 
When reading a longer text in a foreign language it is often helpful to read the headings first, 
especially when you know what information you're looking for. 
Try using this strategy for the next few questions.

If you attend the Fringe Festival, you’ll see a variety of different spectacles.
hard to predict

 frightfully funny 
It is an intensifier phrase meaning “very funny”. 
It is used in this text because the two “f” sounds within the word sound good. 
Intensifiers in English can emphasise without changing meaning.

utterly packed... ...means very full of stuff.
totally free... ...means it costs nothing at all.
quite small... ...means not very big.

The festival is completely open, which means that absolutely anyone can perform.

