5. Developing fluency - Use the second conditional

If I were you, I'd wear a suit.
"if I were" sounds more hypothetical than "if I was" and is more common.

We would invite plus ones if the venue were bigger.
If I had time, I would come to the party this weekend.
I would be at the wedding if I could.
Joe would know what time the wedding starts, if he looked at the invitation.
If I had another party, I wouldn't choose this caterer again.
He would visit his parents more often.

